1.When would you want to use a remote repository rather than keeping all your work local?
	When you want to share your work and collaborate with other people.
2.Why might you want to always pull changes manually rather than having Git automatically stay up-to-date with your remote repository?
	Cause you might be finishing a project or something that wouldn't make sense to have in Github before is finished
3.Describe the differences between forks, clones, and branches. When would you use one instead of another?
	A fork is a copy of a repository in github to your remote repository. A clone is a copy of a repository in github to your local repository
	a branch is another serie of commits. 
4.What is the benefit of having a copy of the last known state of the remote stored locally?
	The benefit is that you can merge files when there are two different modifications one in the local and the other in the remote.
5.How would you collaborate without using Git or GitHub? What would be easier, and what would be harder?
	Sending zips to evarybody. It would be easy not to study how github works but eventually harder.
	